SIMPLE: desultory
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Desultory
<hw>Des"ul*to*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>desultorius</ets>, fr. <ets>desultor</ets> a leaper, fr.
<ets>desilire</ets>, <ets>desultum</ets>, to leap down; <ets>de</ets> +
<ets>salire</ets> to leap. See <er>Saltation</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Leaping or skipping about.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I shot at it [a bird], but it was so <qex>desultory</qex> that I
missed my aim.</q> <rj><qau>Gilbert White.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Jumping, or passing, from one thing or subject to
another, without order or rational connection; without logical sequence;
disconnected; immethodical; aimless; <as>as, <ex>desultory</ex>
minds</as>.</def> <rj><au>Atterbury.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He [Goldsmith] knew nothing accurately; his reading had been
<qex>desultory</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Out of course; by the way; as a digression; not
connected with the subject; <as>as, a <ex>desultory</ex>
remark</as>.</def></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Rambling; roving; immethodical; discursive;
inconstant; unsettled; cursory; slight; hasty; loose.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Desume</ent>⟦br⟧
